Introduction¶

Data can be found on several metrics of health, economy, and society of countries. In this report, we will look at four areas of development:

  • Income = Gross Domestic Product (GDP) per capita measured in US dollars per person
  • Human Development Index (HDI) = a measure of a country's progress in achieve standards of health, education, and living measured on a scale of 0 (no achievement) to 1 (perfect achievement)
  • Inequality = Gini Coefficient, a measure of inequality in a country's distribution of wealth and capital measured on a scale of 0 (perfect equality) to 100 (complete inequality)
  • Health of Population and Environment = consists of measures of Average BMI, Average Life Expectancy, and CO2 Emissions for a country

Using data from the Gapminder Database, this study will explore the following questions:¶

Q1: What is the relationship between economic development and human development (education, health, and living standards)? Scope: 1990 to 2015¶

Q2: What is the relationship between economic development and inequality? Scope: 1980 to 2020¶

Q3: What is the relationship between economic development and the health of the population and the environment? Scope: 1980 to 2008¶

DATA REQUIREMENTS

  • INCOME 1980-2020
  • HDI 1990-2015 LIMITING FACTOR FOR Question 1
  • GINI 1980-2020 LIMITED to Modern Era (1980 - 2020 for comparison) for Question 2
  • LIFE 1980-2008
  • BMI 1980-2008
  • CO2 1980-2008 LIMITING FACTOR FOR Question 3

CO2 Data seems to have significant gaps in the 1800's. Because this data will be compared with BMI (1980-2008), we will only explore this data set beginning at 1980.¶

Data Cleaning: Getting the correct data ranges (Working within Limitations)¶

From the investigations above, the following limitations have been found:

  • Q1: economic and human development is limited to the years 1990 to 2015 due to the availability of the Human Development Index (HDI) data
  • Q2: economic and inequality data is available from 1800 to beyond our current time (extrapolated data), but will be limited to 1980 to 2020 to focus on the current era.
  • Q3: economic, health, and environmental data is limited to the years 1980 to 2008 (due to the limitations on BMI 1980-2008 and inconsistent CO2 data before 1980 and CO2 data that ends in 2014)

For simplicity we will pull preliminary data at 1980, 1990, and 2000 for comparison to modern data.¶

Modern data will be pulled from the given years for the respective datasets:¶

  • 2008 (income, BMI, life expectancy, CO2 emissions - Question 3)
  • 2010 (provided for consistent decade analysis with earlier data)
  • 2015 (income, Human Development Index - Question 1)
  • 2020 (Income, Gini - Question 2)

These modern years were chosen based on the availability of the data.¶

To better analyze data across quartiles of incomes, the following functions were written.

  • set_quart_bounds takes a year as an agrument and then returns the 5-point summary for income for the requested year as a list. This is helpful in separating the data into income quartiles.
  • get_income_quarts takes a year as an argument and then returns 4 subsets of the complete dataframe, one for each quartile of income for the requested year, as a list. Dependencies: uses set_quart_bounds to get the appropriate boundary values for income quartiles.
  • get_bar_heights takes a year and another metric from the complete dataframe as an argument and returns the average value of that metric for each of the four quartiles of income for that year. Dependencies: uses get_income_quarts to break the complete dataframe into the appropriate sets.

For example, get_bar_heights(2000,'bmi') would return a list of four values, the average of 'bmi_2000' for each income quartile in the year 2000.

In [67]:
# define fuction for finding the bounds of income quartiles
def set_quart_bounds(year):
    # return a list containing the five-number summary of income for the given year
    return [complete_df.min()['income_'+str(year)], complete_df.quantile(.25)['income_'+str(year)], complete_df.median()['income_'+str(year)], complete_df.quantile(.75)['income_'+str(year)], complete_df.max()['income_'+str(year)]]

# define function for finding the groups that make each income quartile
def get_income_quarts(year):
    # get the bounds from the previous function
    bounds = set_quart_bounds(year)
    # create each quartile by query (searching for income's between each set of bounds)
    quart1 = complete_df.query('income_{0} >= {1} and income_{0} <= {2}'.format(year, bounds[0], bounds[1]))
    quart2 = complete_df.query('income_{0} > {1} and income_{0} <= {2}'.format(year, bounds[1],bounds[2]))
    quart3 = complete_df.query('income_{0} > {1} and income_{0} <= {2}'.format(year, bounds[2],bounds[3]))
    quart4 = complete_df.query('income_{0} > {1} and income_{0} <= {2}'.format(year, bounds[3],bounds[4]))
    # returns a list of the dataframes that make up each quartile
    return [quart1, quart2, quart3, quart4]

# find the mean of a specific metric for each of the four income quartiles
def get_bar_heights(year, metric):
    # get the quartiles for the given year
    quarts = get_income_quarts(year)
    # properly format the metric name according to dataframe column names
    mtr = '{}_{}'.format(metric, year)
    # return the mean value of the given metric for each income quartile
    return [quarts[0].mean()[mtr], quarts[1].mean()[mtr], quarts[2].mean()[mtr], quarts[3].mean()[mtr]]

Another function definition to help with analysis. The function is described below:

  • income_quart_bar_graph takes two years and a metric to produce side-by-side bar graphs of that average metric for each income quartile for the requested years. Dependencies: uses get_bar_heights to get the appropriate values of the metric for each of the quartiles for each year.
In [76]:
# define a function that will give a side-by-side comparison of a metric over income quartiles and time
def income_quart_bar_graph(year1, year2, metric):
    # set the width of each bar
    width = 0.3
    # make a list that represents placement of the bars for the first year
    loc_A = np.arange(1, 5, 1)
    # use get_bar_heights to get the mean values of the metric for each income quartile
    heights_A = get_bar_heights(year1, metric)
    # make a list that represents placement of the bars for the second year
    loc_B = np.arange(1 + width, 5, 1)
    # use get_bar_heights to get the mean values of the metric for each income quartile
    heights_B = get_bar_heights(year2, metric)
    # make a list that represents placement of the labels between the bars
    loc_label = np.arange(1 + width/2, 5, 1)
    # make the bar graph for the first year
    plt.bar(loc_A, heights_A, width)
    # make the bar graph for the second year
    plt.bar(loc_B, heights_B, width)
    # label the bars for their respective income quartile
    labels = ['0-25%ile','25-50%ile','50-75%ile','75-100%ile']
    plt.xticks(loc_label, labels)
    plt.xlabel('Quartile of Income (GDP per capita)')
    # show a legend of years represented in the graph
    plt.legend([year1, year2]);
In [77]:

plt.ylabel('Average BMI (kg/m^2)');

Conclusions¶

Q1: What is the relationship between economic development and human development (education, health, and living standards)?¶

A strong relationship exists between a country's economic development (US$/person) and its ability to achieve the Human Development Index's (HDI) metrics of health, education, and living standards.

In additon to the progress afforded by economic development, most countries have made gains in their Human Development between 1990 and 2015 due to factors that are outside of the scope of this analysis.

Q2: What is the relationship between economic development and inequality?¶

There is no significant relationship between economic development and inequality (as measured by the Gini coefficient), though there is one pattern worth exploring in further analysis. High inequality (high Gini coefficient) is more prevalent in countries with lower income and absent from countries with higher income.

Overall, the measure of inequality is coverging on an average of 40 over time, with the spread shrinking from 1980 to 2020.

Q3: What is the relationship between economic development and the health of the population and the environment?¶

There is a strong, logarithmic relationship between a country's income and the BMI and life expectancy of that country. There are more outliers in this relationship than the previous questions, but the relationship still demonstrates higher BMI and life expectancy for countries with higher income.

There is strong, linear relationship between a country's income and its CO2 emissions. This demonstrates a link between the size of a country's economy and the amount of CO2 that is released per person in that country.

Limitations¶

Exclusion of smaller and developing countries without an HDI score in 1990.¶

52 countries were dropped from the analysis due to the lack of a Human Development Index Score in 1990. Excluding these countries due to their status in 1990 may have skewed the data toward higher income and more developed countries for the modern analysis. It may also have limited the analysis of "growth" as measured in the report, due to the likely gains made by the smaller or developing countries after 1990.

Analysis from 'per capita' basis.¶

Analyzing CO2 emissions and income on a 'per capita' basis did not account for the population of those countries. While it may establish a strong person-to-person comparison, it did not allow for a comparison of total impact (total GDP or CO2 emissions for given countries). Including population in the analysis may have also allowed a deeper understanding of the measures of inequality such as Gini coefficient or Human Development Index.

Comparing years vs. trends¶

The analysis in this report compared statistics and metrics from selected years, instead of analyzing more complex trends over time. Year comparison analysis can establish patterns, but does not provide a narrative of what happened between those years. It is also limited to the available data, which causes the year of analysis to shift depending on the variables and limits the overall coherence of the findings.
